            "content": "# Ledger Documentation Overhaul Plan\n\n## Context\n\nThe Ledger codebase has inconsistent documentation quality. Some files (filters.h,\namount.h, balance.h) have excellent Doxygen documentation, while most .cc files and\nmany headers lack function-level docs, code group explanations, or architectural\ncontext. The manual (ledger3.texi) uses a conversational, educational voice that\nshould be echoed in source comments. This plan creates harmony across source comments,\nmanual, manpage, and README.\n\n## Approach\n\n**Core layers first**, tackled one architectural layer per session. Each layer gets:\n- Rich Doxygen documentation (file headers, class docs, function docs, code groups)\n- Cross-checked against manual/manpage for consistency (flagging and fixing mismatches)\n- Voice aligned with the manual's educational, \"why before what\" style\n\n**Documentation Standard** (modeled after filters.h and amount.h):\n- Every file: `@file` / `@brief` / `@ingroup` header with architectural context\n- Every class: `@class` / `@brief` with purpose and design rationale\n- Every public function: `@brief`, `@param` / `@return` where non-obvious\n- Large functions: code group comments explaining logical sections\n- Connection to user-facing behavior where relevant\n\n## Session Execution Order\n\n### Session 1 (THIS SESSION): Core Data Model\n**Files**: amount.h/cc, value.h/cc, balance.h/cc, commodity.h/cc, pool.h/cc, annotate.h/cc\n**~8,250 lines** | These are the mathematical foundation\n\n- [ ] Review existing docs in amount.h (already good) as the gold standard\n- [ ] Document value.cc (2,256 lines, largest file, currently sparse)\n- [ ] Document balance.cc (433 lines, moderate)\n- [ ] Document commodity.h/cc and pool.h/cc\n- [ ] Document annotate.h/cc\n- [ ] Cross-check: verify manual's \"Commodities\" chapter matches code behavior\n- [ ] Cross-check: verify manpage --basis, --market, --exchange descriptions\n\n### Session 2: Journal Model\n**Files**