ance rationale comments\n\n### Step 4: Document balance.cc (433 lines)\n- Multi-commodity arithmetic explanation\n- How balance interacts with amount and value\n\n### Step 5: Document commodity.h/cc and pool.h/cc\n- Commodity definition and formatting rules\n- Pool singleton and commodity lifecycle\n- Cross-check with manual's \"Commodities\" section\n\n### Step 6: Document annotate.h/cc\n- Cost basis tracking\n- Lot pricing annotation system\n\n### Step 7: Cross-Reference Check\n- Compare code behavior with manual sections on commodities, amounts, values\n- Compare with manpage descriptions of --basis, --market, --exchange, --gain\n- Flag and fix any inconsistencies\n\n## Voice Guidelines\n\nMatch the manual's style adapted for source comments:\n- **Educational**: Explain \"why\" this code exists, not just \"what\" it does\n- **Grounded in accounting**: Use terms like \"posting\", \"transaction\", \"commodity\" naturally\n- **Concise but complete**: Every comment earns its place\n- **Connected**: Reference related code and user-facing behavior\n- **Example**: Instead of \"// converts values\" write:\n  ```\n  /// @brief Convert a balance to a single commodity using market prices.\n  ///\n  /// When a user runs `ledger bal --exchange USD`, balances containing\n  /// multiple commodities must be converted to a single target.  This\n  /// method applies the most recent price from the commodity history\n  /// to produce a unified amount.\n  ```\n\n## Verification\n\nAfter each session:\n1. Build the project: `cd build && make -j$(nproc)` — docs must not break compilation\n2. Run Doxygen if configured to verify doc generation\n3. Spot-check that cross-referenced manual sections still align\n4. Review baseline tests for the documented layer to confirm behavioral accuracy\n",
